        <h1 class="text-4xl font-bold tracking-tight mb-4 leading-tight">Fire Extinguisher Inspection in Long Beach, CA: What Every Business Owner Needs to Know</h1>
        <p class="text-lg text-gray-500 leading-relaxed mb-8">If you own or manage a commercial property in Long Beach, CA, your fire extinguishers are a legal requirement with specific inspection schedules enforced by the Long Beach Fire Department. Here's exactly what NFPA 10 and the California Fire Code (Title 19 CCR) require, what inspections cost, and how to avoid violations.</p>
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold tracking-tight mb-3">Long Beach Fire Extinguisher Requirements</h2>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">The City of Long Beach enforces the California Fire Code (Title 19 CCR), requiring all commercial properties to maintain portable fire extinguishers in compliance with <a href="/compliance/nfpa-10/" class="text-red-brand hover:underline">NFPA 10: Standard for Portable Fire Extinguishers</a>. Long Beach is home to one of the world's busiest seaports, creating a commercial landscape that combines waterfront hotel and restaurant operations with significant port-adjacent industrial and logistics facilities. Cold storage warehouses near the port may require specialized Class B extinguisher coverage for ammonia refrigeration hazards. Long Beach's marine environment — salt air and humidity — accelerates corrosion on extinguisher hardware, particularly in port-adjacent facilities and buildings near the waterfront.</p>
        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold mb-3">Monthly Visual Inspections</h3>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">Monthly visual inspections can be performed by trained building staff — no license required. Verify each extinguisher is in its designated location, unobstructed, the pressure gauge reads in the operating range, and the tamper seal and pull pin are intact. Document every check. Absence of monthly records significantly increases liability exposure in the event of an incident or enforcement action.</p>
        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold mb-3">Annual Professional Inspections</h3>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">Annual inspections must be performed by a licensed technician who inspects mechanical parts, agent condition, pressure gauge, hose and nozzle, and attaches a dated service tag. California requires fire extinguisher service contractors to hold an OSFM license from the California State Fire Marshal's Office. Verify your provider's OSFM license at osfm.fire.ca.gov before scheduling service. Any failed unit must be immediately serviced, recharged, or replaced.</p>
        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold mb-3">6-Year Internal Examination</h3>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">Every six years, stored-pressure extinguishers must be emptied, disassembled, and internally examined for corrosion and agent degradation. This typically includes a full recharge after examination. Missing the 6-year exam is frequently cited during Long Beach Fire Department commercial property inspections.</p>
        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold mb-3">12-Year Hydrostatic Testing</h3>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">At 12 years, extinguisher cylinders must pass hydrostatic pressure testing to verify structural integrity. Units that fail must be condemned and cannot be returned to service. Budget for some units to require replacement at this interval.</p>
